<font color="#FF0000">TOILET FLUSHING &amp; DEMI MOORE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Aug 25 22:36:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed, you're only saying that on account Demi Moore became a Special Forces Navy Seal. <br>
Barry, she was not a Marine.  She went from stripper to Navy Seal (same same), that's why they like those tight leather suits. <br><br>
I know Humming Eagle is only saying those things above because he wants to impress her. Well, Ed we wouldn't even let JOHN WAYNE join our platoon. <br><br>
When Chesty Puller the most decorated Marine in all of history who used to say you ain't a Marine until you've done time in the brig, when he came to Nam he visted all the combat and special forces camps in the North and in South Vietnam including Watts and Disneyland he said, ok now take me to 1st platoon , India Company 3/7 1st Marine Division, and Hill 65 where the real fighting men are. But when he didn't have the 25 cents fee to ride the chopper kiddie-ride, in honor of you Ed, we wouldn't let him get on free.<br>
 <br>
But you did remind me of a REAL STORY.<br><br>
From Dreams of Glory, Clear fields of Fire, (unedited) Copyright 1997, Cook Barela <br><br>
1st Medical Hospital<br>
DaNang, South Viet Nam<br>
November 28th, 1967<br><br>
We rode out the following morning on a six-by truck that took fifteen of us into DaNang's 1st Medical hospital. Seven of us at the hospital were causalities of Jungle rot, some had come from the 3rd Marine Division. Marines who like myself had been out in the field for weeks without having the time to take off their boots much less change socks. <br>
We soon gathered around and begin to compare the color and the smell of our feet as well and the various stages of the infection. Soon we were comparing other diseases we had encountered in Nam. Malaria, leprosy, and all kinds of social diseases.  We compared the marks left behind by insect bites, the size and the color of the puss some had   received around their eyes from insect bites.<br>
We spoke about the size of and the different colored snakes some had seen or been biten by. We spoke about the different and weird animals and the multi-colored and noisy birds we had seen. We spoke of the largest rats we had killed and how many roosters, chickens, dogs and rock apes we had shot. We spoke of the rounds it took to bring down a large size water buffalo. We went from there to the type of food we had eaten, which included large insects, wild boars, snakes, dog, rats, monkeys, water buffalo, pigs, chicken, ducks and brown husked rice that moved. We shared stories about gorillas, monkeys, elephants and tigers that had been encountered in the bush. We spoke about the disease caused by leeches when they were plugged off and they left their heads  imbedded under the skin. Some Marines even spoke about the war and the dead chinese, and Russian advisors they had killed,  gooks they had seen or killed and the many colorful clothes and different uniforms they had seen them wear. Tall ones, skinny ones, fat ones, stinky ones, and the women that had followed their men into battle and how some had died alongside them. <br>
While we sat around talking a Marine from the 3rd Marine Division got up and walked into the adjoining room looking for the head. He had been in Viet Nam for over eight months and most of that time it had been in some remote post out on the fringes of civilization. A couple of minutes after he had left the group we heard a loud scream. <br>
We rushed over to see what was going on and on the way there we heard him scream again. The scream was loud and full of anguish. As we went through a set of double doors we found him sitting on the floor next to a commode. <br><br>
He pulled down the toilets handle and the water flushed and he screamed again.<br>
It had been so long since he had seen a toilet that pushing the commodes flush handle gave him great pleasure. It was civilization, it represented home, it was as American as ice cream and apple pie and it gave all of us a sense of the real world and life and gave us a reason for living.<br><br>
It's funny how such simple things like a toilet can be taken for granted and how we don't realize what comfort we had back in the real world until one has to do without. It had been five months since I had last seen a toilet and I could easily associate with the joy that Marine  was feeling and the high he was getting just sitting there on the floor flushing the toilet. He must have flushed it twenty-thirthy times before he was satisfied that it was real and that it wasn't going away. We then took turns flushing the toilet. Flushing that toilet was more therapeutic then a whole week of physic counseling. We stood in line to flush that toilet. It was our rites of passage, it was the re-introduction we needed to turn our minds back toward the real world. I guess John was right when he told me shortly before he left Viet Nam. <br><br>
&quot;For those who have fought for it, life has a flavor the protected will never know.&quot; <br><br>
A new young medical Navy doctor that was making his rounds came by to see what was going on. He walked away shaking his head and muttering to himself; <br>
&quot;Awe be damned, Crazy, Crazy Marines. 
